{"parse":{"title":"break","pageid":6806,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Break}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|brāk|a=RP,GA,CA}}, {{IPA|en|/bɹeɪk/|[bɹʷeɪ̯k]}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-break.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-break.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/bɹɛk/|a=Northumbrian}}\n* {{i|obsolete}} {{enPR|brēk}}, {{IPA|en|/bɹiːk/}}<ref>{{R:Jespersen MEGoHP|I|11.75|339}}</ref>\n* {{IPA|en|/brɛːk/|a=Early Modern|ref={{R:en:Dobson:1957|II|115|625|passage=The sixteenth and seventeenth-century orthoepists do not distinguish ''great'', ''break'', ''steak'', and ''yea'' from other ME ''ę̄'' words.}}}}\n* {{IPA|en|/bɹæɪk/|a=AU,NZ}}\n* {{homophones|en|brake}}\n* {{rhymes|en|eɪk|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:breken|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|breken}}, from {{inh|en|ang|brecan||to break}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*brekan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*brekaną||to break}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*bʰreg-||to break}}. {{doublet|en|bray}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognates of Germanic origin include {{cog|sco|brek||to break}}, {{cog|fy|brekke||to break}}, {{cog|nl|breken||to break}}, {{cog|nds|breken||to break}}, {{cog|de|brechen||to break}}, {{cog|fr|broyer||to crush, grind}}, {{cog|got|𐌱𐍂𐌹𐌺𐌰𐌽|t=to break, destroy}}, {{cog|no|brek||desire, yearning}}.\n\nAlso cognate with {{cog|sq|brishtë||fragile}}, {{cog|la|frangō||break, break up, shatter|pos=verb}}, whence {{cog|en|fracture}} and other terms – {{m|en|fragile}}, {{m|en|frail}}, {{m|en|fraction}}, and {{m|en|fragment}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\nThe modern pronunciation shows an irregular change of Early Modern English {{IPAchar|/ɛː/}} to {{IPAchar|/eɪ/}} in the standard language; contrast this with the development of other words such as {{m|en|speak}} and {{m|en|wreak}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|~s|~ing|broke,brake<l:archaic>|broken,broke<l:nonstandard>}}\n\n# {{lb|en|ergative|transitive|intransitive}} To [[separate]] into two or more [[piece]]s, to [[fracture]] or [[crack]], by a process that cannot easily be [[reverse]]d for [[reassembly]].\n#: {{ux|en|If the vase falls to the floor, it might '''break'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|In order to tend to the accident victim, he will '''break''' the window of the car.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=8 May 2012|page=79|title=Ottolenghi: The Cookbook|author=w:Yotam Ottolenghi; Sami Tamimi|publisher=w:Random House|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=WFzJR9ZZ7aEC|isbn=9781446407097|passage=First, marinate the tofu. In a bowl, whisk the kecap manis, chilli sauce, and sesame oil together. Cut the tofu into strips about 1cm thick, mix gently (so it doesn't '''break''') with the marinade and leave in the fridge for half an hour.}}\n## {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[crack]] or [[fracture]] (bone) under a [[physical]] [[strain]].\n##: {{ux|en|His ribs '''broke''' under the weight of the rocks piled on his chest.}}\n##: {{ux|en|He slipped on the ice and '''broke''' his leg.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[divide]] (something, often [[money]]) into smaller units.\n#: {{ux|en|Can you '''break''' a hundred-dollar bill for me?}}\n#: {{ux|en|The wholesaler '''broke''' the container loads into palettes and boxes for local retailers.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause (a person or animal) to lose [[spirit]] or [[will]]; to [[crush]] the spirits of.\n#: {{ux|en|Her child’s death '''broke''' Angela.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Interrogators have used many forms of torture to '''break''' prisoners of war.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The interrogator hoped to '''break''' her to get her testimony against her accomplices.}}\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|Job|9|16|17|If I had called, and had answered me, yet would I not beleeue that he had hearkened vnto my voice: For he '''breaketh''' me with a tempest, and multiplieth my wounds without cause.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 8|IV|2|text=An old man, '''broken''' with the storms of state,<br>Is come to lay his weary bones among ye;<br>Give him a little earth for charity}}\n## To turn an [[animal]] into a [[beast of burden]].\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=2002|author=w:John Fusco|title={{w|Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron}}\n|passage=Colonel: See, gentlemen? Any horse could be '''broken'''.}}\n##: {{ux|en|You have to '''break''' an elephant before you can use it as an animal of burden.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be [[crush]]ed, or [[overwhelmed]] with [[sorrow]] or [[grief]].\n#: {{ux|en|My heart is '''breaking'''.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=1 Feb 86|volume=13|number=28|journal=Gay Community News|page=5|author=Kathy Jo Elliott|title=Solid As A Rock|text=Two days later they transferred her to another prison to separate us. I '''broke'''. My life was gone, so I thought.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[interrupt]]; to [[destroy]] the [[continuity]] of; to [[dissolve]] or [[terminate]].\n#: {{ux|en|I’ve got to '''break''' this habit I have of biting my nails.}}\n#: {{co|en|to '''break''' silence; to '''break''' one's sleep; to '''break''' one’s journey}}\n#: {{ux|en|I had won four games in a row, but now you've '''broken''' my streak of luck.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|V|i|passage=Go, release them, Ariel; / My charms I'll '''break''', their senses I'll restore.}}\n## {{lb|en|transitive|theatre}} To end the run of (a play).\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1958|author=Walter Macqueen-Pope|title=St. James's: Theatre of Distinction|page=134\n|passage=In July Alexander '''broke''' the run and went on tour, as was his custom. He believed in keeping in touch with provincial audiences and how wise he was!}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1986|author=Kurt Gänzl|title=The British Musical Theatre: 1865-1914|page=610\n|passage=After Camberwell he '''broke''' the play's season and brought it back in the autumn with a few revisions and a noticeably strengthened cast but without any special success.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[ruin]] [[financially]].\n#: {{ux|en|The recession '''broke''' some small businesses.}}\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Juvenal Satires|7|passage=With arts like these rich Matho, when he speaks, / Attracts all fees, and little lawyers '''breaks'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[fail]] in [[business]]; to go [[broke]], to become [[bankrupt]].\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Essayes|chapter=Of Riches|passage=He that puts all upon adventures doth oftentimes '''break''', and come to poverty.}}\n#* '''1791-92''', {{w|Jane Austen}}, ‘A Collection of Letters’, ''Juvenilia'':\n#*: ‘I knew he was in some such low way—He '''broke''' did not he?’\n# {{lb|en|finance|intransitive}} Of [[price]]s on the [[stock exchange]]: to [[fall]] suddenly.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2008|author=George Angell|title=Small Stocks for Big Profits\n|passage=With a few exceptions, stock prices tend to follow the overall market averages. When you have a market decline, therefore, many stocks share the same overall chart pattern. Prices '''break''' and go sideways for a period of time.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[violate]]; to fail to [[adhere]] to.\n#: {{ux|en|When you go to Vancouver, promise me you won't '''break''' the law.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He '''broke''' his vows by cheating on his wife.}}\n#: {{co|en|to '''break''' one’s word}}\n#: {{ux|en|Time travel would '''break''' the laws of physics.}}\n#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Regained|book=Samson Agonistes|48|lines=749–751|passage=Out, out ''Hyæna''; theſe are thy wonted arts, [...] To '''break''' all faith, all vows, deceive, betray,}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a fever}} To go [[down]], in terms of [[temperature]], [[indicate|indicating]] that the most [[dangerous]] part of the [[illness]] has [[pass]]ed.\n#: {{ux|en|Susan's fever '''broke''' at about 3 AM, and the doctor said the worst was over.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a|_|spell of settled|_|weather}} To [[end]].\n#: {{ux|en|The forecast says the hot weather will '''break''' by midweek.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a|_|storm}} To [[begin]] or [[end]].\n#: {{ux|en|We ran to find shelter before the storm '''broke'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Around midday the storm '''broke''', and the afternoon was calm and sunny.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of morning, dawn, day etc.}} To [[arrive]].\n#: {{ux|en|Morning has '''broken'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The day '''broke''' crisp and clear.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|II|ii|passage=The day begins to '''break''', and night is fled.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|gaming|_|slang}} To [[render]] (a game) [[unchallenging]] by [[altering]] its [[rule]]s or [[exploit]]ing [[loophole]]s or [[weakness]]es in them in a way that gives a [[player]] an [[unfair]] [[advantage]].\n#: {{ux|en|Changing the rules to let white have three extra queens would '''break''' chess.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I '''broke''' the RPG by training every member of my party to cast fireballs as well as use swords.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[stop]], or to cause to stop, [[function]]ing [[properly]] or [[altogether]].\n#: {{ux|en|On the hottest day of the year the refrigerator '''broke'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Did you two '''break''' the trolley by racing with it?}}\n## {{lb|en|specifically|in|_|programming}} To cause (some [[feature]] of a [[program]] or piece of [[software]]) to [[stop]] [[function]]ing [[properly]]; to cause a [[regression]].\n##: {{ux|en|Adding 64-bit support '''broke''' backward compatibility with earlier versions.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause (a [[barrier]]) to no longer [[bar]].\n#: {{co|en|to '''break''' a seal}}\n## {{lb|en|specifically}} To cause the [[shell]] of (an [[egg]]) to [[crack]], so that the [[inside]] ([[yolk]]) is [[accessible]].\n## {{lb|en|specifically}} To [[open]] (a [[safe]]) without using the [[correct]] [[key]], [[combination]]{{,}} or the like.\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1992|artist={{w|Alice in Chains|Alice in Chains}}|title={{w|Dirt (Alice in Chains album)|Rain When I Die}}|passage=I'm a riddle so strong, you can't '''break''' me}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[destroy]] the [[arrangement]] of; to [[throw]] into [[disorder]]; to [[pierce]].\n#: {{ux|en|The cavalry were not able to '''break''' the British squares.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a wave of water}} To collapse into [[surf]], after arriving in [[shallow]] water. [[Image:A storm at Pors-Loubous.jpg|right|thumb|196px|A wave '''breaking'''.]]\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1966|director={{w|Bruce Brown (director)|Bruce Brown}}|title={{w|The Endless Summer}}|text=There are many places on the reef that '''break''' during the summer.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[burst forth]]; to make its way; to come into [[view]].\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Metamorphoses|book=I|section=The Gyants War|page=16|passage=The Clouds are ſtill above; and, while I ſpeak, / A ſecond deluge o'er our head may '''break'''.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1800|author=w:William Wordsworth|title=[[s:Lyrical Ballads (1800)/Volume 2/The Fountain|The Fountain]]\n|passage=And from the turf a fountain '''broke''', / And gurgled at our feet.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[interrupt]] or [[cease]] one's [[work]] or [[occupation]] [[temporarily]]; to go on [[#Noun|break]].\n#: {{ux|en|Let's '''break''' for lunch.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[interrupt]] (a [[fall]]) by [[insert]]ing something so that the falling object does not (immediately) [[hit]] something else [[beneath]].\n#: {{ux|en|He survived the jump out the window because the bushes below '''broke''' his fall.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|ergative}} To [[disclose]] or [[make known]] an item of [[news]], a [[band]], etc.\n#: {{ux|en|The newsman wanted to '''break''' a big story, something that would make him famous.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I don’t know how to '''break''' this to you, but your cat is not coming back.}}\n#: {{ux|en|When news of their divorce '''broke'''...}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2010|author=Jon Kutner; Spencer Leigh|title=1,000 UK Number One Hits\n|passage=Herman's Hermits version of 'I'm Into Something Good' topped the UK charts and also '''broke''' the band in the States.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2023-03-08|author=Jonathan Tannenwald|title=CBS is launching a 24/7 soccer channel online|journal=w:The Philadelphia Inquirer|url=https://www.inquirer.com/soccer/cbs-sports-soccer-live-streaming-golazo-network-20230308.html|passage=“If something '''breaks''' during the day, work hours up until the evening, we’ll cut in — if we’re in the middle of, let’s say, a magazine program or a podcast on tape or a re-air of the game,” Radovich said.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a [[sound]]}} To become [[audible]] [[suddenly]].\n#* {{circa|1843}}, {{w|George Lippard}}, ''The Battle-Day of Germantown'', reprinted in ''Washington and His Generals \"1776\"'', page 45&nbsp;[http://google.com/books?id=EM-qNjWrI9YC&pg=PA45&dq=%22sound+of+musquetry%22]:\n#*: Like the crash of thunderbolts[...], the sound of musquetry '''broke''' over the lawn, [...].\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[change]] a [[steady]] [[state]] [[abrupt]]ly.\n#: {{ux|en|His coughing '''broke''' the silence.}}\n#: {{ux|en|His turning on the lights '''broke''' the enchantment.}}\n#: {{ux|en|With the mood '''broken''', what we had been doing seemed pretty silly.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|with '''for'''}} To (attempt to) [[disengage]] and [[flee]] to; to [[make a run for it|make a run for]].\n#* {{quote-av|en|author=Drachinifel|title=Last Ride of the High Seas Fleet - Battle of Texel 1918|date=17 October 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YrTeYcRXDEw|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20220804035059/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YrTeYcRXDEw|archivedate=4 August 2022|accessdate=4 August 2022|time=26:02|text=As the last firing of the big guns begins to die down, the German light forces still fighting to the west begin to make their choices.  Some '''break''' for the open sea; others run for the German-occupied coast; still others stand and die.  A small group decide to strike their colors, in imitation of three of the larger German ships.}}\n# {{lb|en|copulative|informal}} To [[suddenly]] [[become]].\n#: {{ux|en|Things began '''breaking''' bad for him when his parents died.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The arrest was standard, when suddenly the suspect '''broke''' ugly.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a [[male]] [[voice]]}} To become [[deep]]er at [[puberty]].\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a [[voice]]}} To [[alter]] in type due to [[emotion]] or [[strain]]: in [[men]], generally to go [[up]], in [[women]], sometimes to go [[down]]; to [[crack]].\n#: {{ux|en|His voice '''breaks''' when he gets emotional.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a [[sauce]] or [[emulsion]]}} To [[de-emulsify]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004|title=Encyclopedia of supramolecular chemistry|volume=2|page=1466|author=J. L. Atwood; Jonathan W. Steed|passage=Conversely, as the emulsion '''breaks''' and the system returns to the original state, energy is released.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=pcQSir2QXbMC}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Emulsions and emulsion stability|volume=22|author=Johan Sjöblom|page=400|year=2006|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vcNWGexVc4cC|passage=When the droplets hit a solid wall the emulsion '''breaks''' instantly forming a bitumen on the wall and thus a layer up to 1 cm thick can be sprayed in one operation without requiring drying in between.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[surpass]] or do [[better]] than (a [[specific]] [[number]]); to do [[better]] than (a [[record]]), setting a new record.\n#: {{ux|en|He '''broke''' the men's 100-meter record.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I can't believe she '''broke''' 3 under par!}}\n#: {{ux|en|The policeman '''broke''' sixty on a residential street in his hurry to catch the thief.}}\n# {{lb|en|sports|and|games}}:\n## {{lb|en|transitive|tennis}} To [[win]] a [[game]] (against one's [[opponent]]) as [[receiver]].\n##: {{ux|en|He needs to '''break''' serve to win the match.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=June 28, 2012|author=Jamie Jackson|title=Wimbledon 2012: Lukas Rosol shocked by miracle win over Rafael Nadal|work=the Guardian|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/jun/28/rafael-nadal-lukas-rosol-wimbledon-2012?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487|passage=Yet when play restarted the Czech was a train that kept on running over Nadal. After '''breaking''' Nadal in the opening game of the final set, he went 2-0 up and later took the count to 4-2 with yet another emphatic ace – one of his 22 throughout.}}\n## {{lb|en|intransitive|billiards|snooker|pool}} To make the [[first]] [[shot]]; to [[scatter]] the [[ball]]s from the [[initial]] [[neat]] [[arrangement]].\n##: {{ux|en|Is it your or my turn to '''break'''?}}\n## {{lb|en|transitive|backgammon}} To [[remove]] one of the two [[man|men]] on (a [[point]]).\n# {{lb|en|transitive|military|most often in the|_|passive tense}} To [[demote]]; to [[reduce]] the [[military]] [[rank]] of.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1926|author=w:T.E. Lawrence|title=Seven Pillars of Wisdom|location=New York|publisher=Anchor|year_published=1991|page=167\n|passage=Sir Reginald Wingate, High Commissioner in Egypt, was happy for the success of the work he had advocated for years. I grudged him this happiness; for McMahon, who took the actual risk of starting it, had been '''broken''' just before prosperity began.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=February 9 1953|title=Books: First Rulers of Asia|titleurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030210729/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,889691,00.html|journal=Time\n|passage=And he played no favorites: when his son-in-law sacked a city he had been told to spare, Genghis '''broke''' him to private.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1968|author=w:William Manchester|title=w:The Arms of Krupp|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=TIsvPMXQEBcC&pg=PA215&dq=broken|page=215|publisher=Back Bay|year_published=2003|isbn=978-0-316-52940-2\n|passage=One morning after the budget had failed to balance Finanzminister von Scholz picked up Der Reichsanzeiger and found he had been '''broken''' to sergeant.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=[[w:Peter Collier (political author)|Peter Collier]]|title=Medal of Honor: Portraits of Valor Beyond the Call of Duty|publisher=Second Edition, Artisan Books|isbn=978-1-57965-314-9|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=EqH-BJ-k0NsC&pg=PA42&dq=broken|page=42\n|passage=Not long after this event, Clausen became involved in another disciplinary situation and was '''broken''' to private—the only one to win the Medal of Honor in Vietnam.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[end]] (a [[connection]]); to [[disconnect]].\n#: {{ux|en|The referee ordered the boxers to '''break''' the clinch.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The referee '''broke''' the boxers' clinch.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I couldn’t hear a thing he was saying, so I '''broke''' the connection and called him back.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|sports}} To [[counter-attack]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 28, 2010|author=Kevin Darlin|title=West Brom 1 - 3 Blackburn|work=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9308862.stm|passage=The Baggies almost hit back instantly when {{w|Graham Dorrans}} '''broke''' from midfield and pulled the trigger from 15 yards but Paul Robinson did superbly to tip the Scot's drive around the post.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[lay ope]]n, as a purpose; to [[disclose]], [[divulge]], or [[communicate]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|V|ii|passage=Katharine, '''break''' thy mind to me.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become [[weakened]] in [[constitution]] or [[faculties]]; to [[lose]] [[health]] or [[strength]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1731|publisher=w:Jonathan Swift|title=s:Verses on His Own Death\n|passage=See how the dean begins to '''break'''; / Poor gentleman he droops apace.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[destroy]] the [[strength]], [[firmness]], or [[consistency]] of.\n#: {{co|en|to '''break''' flax}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[destroy]] the [[official]] [[character]] and [[standing]] of; to [[cashier]]; to [[dismiss]].\n#* '''January 11, 1711''', {{w|Jonathan Swift}}, ''The Examiner'' No. 24\n#*: when I see a great officer '''broke'''.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To make an [[abrupt]] or [[sudden]] [[change]]; to change [[gait]].\n#: {{co|en|to '''break''' into a run or gallop}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|archaic}} To [[fall out]]; to [[terminate]] [[friendship]].\n#* '''c. 1700''' {{w|Jeremy Collier}}, ''On Friendship''\n#*: To '''break''' upon the score of danger or expense is to be mean and narrow-spirited.\n# {{label|en|computing}} To [[terminate]] the [[execution]] of a [[program]] before [[normal]] [[completion]].\n# {{label|en|programming}} To [[suspend]] the [[execution]] of a [[program]] during [[debugging]] so that the [[state]] of the [[program]] can be [[investigate]]d.\n# {{lb|en|computing}} To cause, or allow the occurrence of, a [[line break]].\n#: {{co|en|zero-width non-'''breaking''' space}}\n\n=====Conjugation=====\n{{en-conj|old=1|past=broke|past_ptc=broken}}\n\n=====Quotations=====\n* {{see citations|en}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|ergative: separate into two or more pieces}} {{l|en|burst}}, {{l|en|bust}}, {{l|en|shatter}}, {{l|en|shear}}, {{l|en|smash}}, {{l|en|split}}, {{l|en|bisect}}\n* {{sense|ergative: crack (bone)}} {{l|en|crack}}, {{l|en|fracture}}\n* {{sense|transitive: turn an animal into a beast of burden}} {{l|en|break in}}, {{l|en|subject}}, {{l|en|tame}}\n* {{sense|transitive: do that which is forbidden by}} {{l|en|contravene}}, {{l|en|go against}}, {{l|en|violate}}\n* {{sense|intransitive: stop functioning}} {{l|en|break down}}, {{l|en|bust}}, {{l|en|fail}}, {{l|en|go down}} {{qualifier|of a computer or computer network}}\n\n=====Antonyms=====\n* {{antsense|transitive: cause to end up in two or more pieces}} {{l|en|assemble}}, {{l|en|fix}}, {{l|en|join}}, {{l|en|mend}}, {{l|en|put together}}, {{l|en|repair}}\n* {{antsense|tennis, intransitive: break serve}} {{l|en|hold}}\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n{{col4|en|title=Hyponyms of ''break'' (verb)\n|break a leg\n|break a sweat\n|break apart\n|break away\n|break bad\n|break bread\n|break down <!--(v.)-->\n|break even\n|break ground\n|break in\n|break into\n|break loose\n|break new ground|break one's ass\n|break off\n|break one's fast\n|break open\n|break out\n|break rank\n|break someone's heart\n|break stride\n|break the ice\n|break through\n|break up\n|break wind\n|horsebreaking\n|unbreak| break containment|like breaking sticks\n|break someone's face\n|break one's face\n|break one's neck}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from ''break'' (verb)|the stroke that broke the camel's back| break on|break the wheel|break one's chops\n|break a butterfly on a wheel|break a butterfly on the wheel|tulip-breaking virus|break a butterfly upon a wheel|break a butterfly upon the wheel|break a fly on a wheel|break a fly on the wheel|break a fly upon a wheel|break a fly upon the wheel|break a lance|break and enter|break a promise|break ass|break back|break bulk|break camp|break character|break cover|break edge|break from|break gates|break into a run|break it|break it down|break it to|break luck|break no squares|break on the wheel|break one off|break one's arm patting oneself on the back|break one's back|break one's balls|break one's duck|break one's fall|break one's lance|break one's maiden|break one's neck|break one's promise|break one's stride|break one's word|break ranks|break sheer|break shins|break silence|break someone's back|break someone's balls|break squelch|break the back of|break the bank|break the buck|break the cycle|break the deadlock|break the fourth wall|break the Internet|break the internet|break the mold|break the mould|break the news|break the Sabbath|break the seal|break the silence|break the story|break upon the wheel|break water|break wedlock|break with|break-ax|break-bones|break-even|break-in|break-off|break-promise|break-upper|break-vow|break-wind|make or break|make-and-break|make-before-break|one can't break a stick in a bundle|one can't break a twig in a bundle|one can't break sticks in a bundle|one cannot break a stick in a bundle|one cannot break a twig in a bundle|one cannot break sticks in a bundle|sticks and stones may break my bones|strike-break|you can't break a stick in a bundle|you can't break a twig in a bundle|you can't break sticks in a bundle|you cannot break a stick in a bundle|you cannot break a twig in a bundle|you cannot break sticks in a bundle|breakdance|a stick in a bundle cannot be broken|a twig in a bundle cannot be broken|rules are made to be broken|sticks in a bundle can't be broken|sticks in a bundle cannot be broken|my condom broke|the straw that broke the camel's back|break reality|break the internets|break the interwebs|break the web|prebreak|rebreak|stonebreak|strikebreak|tiebreak|tobreak|unbreakable|windbreak\n|back-breaking\n|bebreak\n|breakage\n|breakdown <!--(n.)-->\n|breakee\n|break free\n|breaker\n|breakle\n|breakneck\n|breaking change\n|breaking ball|breaking capacity|breaking point|breaking strain|breaking wheel|buck breaking|ground-breaking|heart-breaking|hedge-breaking|mold-breaking|mould-breaking|non-breaking|Sabbath-breaking|you can't make an omelette without breaking eggs|break and entry|break reality|break the internets|break the interwebs|break the web\n|breaking news\n|breaking strain\n|breakout\n|break rigor\n|breakthrough\n|break-up\n|forbreak\n|gamebreaking|break with tradition|horsebreaking\n|icebreaker\n|inbreak\n|make-or-break\n|outbreak\n|overbreak\n|upbreak|breakability|breakable|breakaway|breakback|breakbeat|breakbone|breaker bar|breakface|breakfast|breakfront|breakstone|breakthru|breakwater|breakwind|breaky|brickle|brokeback|halterbreak|housebreak\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Verb}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# An instance of breaking something into two or more pieces.\n#: {{syn|en|split}}\n#: {{ux|en|The femur has a clean '''break''' and so should heal easily.}}\n# A [[physical]] [[space]] that [[open up|opens up]] in something or between two things.\n#: {{syn|en|breach|gap|space|Thesaurus:interspace|Thesaurus:hole}}\n#: {{ux|en|The sun came out in a '''break''' in the clouds.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He waited minutes for a '''break''' in the traffic to cross the highway.}}\n# An [[interruption]] of [[continuity]]; [[departure]] from or [[rupture]] with.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=1958 June|title=New Track Layout and Marshalling Yard at Barking|journal=Railway Magazine|page=428|text=Work commenced at 2.30 p.m. on Saturday and continued without '''break''' until 4 a.m. on Monday morning, in the course of which three shifts of upwards of 90 men each and three steam cranes were employed.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-65743967|title=Pita Limjaroenrat: Thai election upstart who vows to be different|date=2023-05-29|author=Jonathan Head|work=BBC|passage=But the young activists of Move Forward outmanoeuvred the older party, and beat many of its candidates, with an imaginative, social media-based campaign offering voters a complete '''break''' with the past, and a different kind of political leadership.}}\n# {{C|en|Rest}} {{senseid|en|rest or pause, usually from work}} A [[rest]] or [[pause]], usually from [[work]].\n#: {{syn|en|shift break|time-out|Thesaurus:pause}}\n#: {{ux|en|Let’s take a five-minute '''break'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|UK|education}} A time for students to talk or play between lessons.\n##: {{syn|en|playtime<q:UK>|recess<q:US>}}\n##* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1983|author={{w|Bill Oddie}}|title=Gone Birding|publisher=Methuen|location=London|page=35|passage=It was playtime - or rather ‘'''break'''’ - and I had brazenly joined in a game of football on the school parade ground.}}\n## A scheduled interval of days or weeks between periods of school instruction; a holiday.\n##: {{co|en|winter '''break''', spring '''break'''}}\n# A short [[holiday]].\n#: {{syn|en|day off|time off|Thesaurus:vacation}}\n#: {{co|en|a weekend '''break''' on the Isle of Wight}}\n# A [[temporary]] [[split]] with a romantic partner.\n#: {{ux|en|I think we need a '''break'''.}}\n# An [[interval]] or [[intermission]] between two parts of a performance, for example a theatre show, broadcast, or sports game.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2010 |author=Chris Whyatt |title=Chelsea 1 - 0 Bolton |work=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9309542.stm |passage=But they marginally improved after the '''break''' as Didier Drogba hit the post.}}\n# {{senseid|en|change}} A significant [[change]] in circumstance, [[attitude]], [[perception]], or [[focus]] of attention.\n#: {{co|en|big '''break'''}}\n#: {{co|en|lucky '''break''', bad '''break'''}}\n#: {{uxi|en|[[them's the breaks|them's the '''breaks''']]}}\n# {{lb|en|finance}} A sudden [[fall]] in [[price]]s on the [[stock exchange]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1947|title=Reports of the Tax Court of the United States|volume=8|page=459\n|passage=Following the invasion of France by the Germans in May of 1940, the securities markets experienced a '''break''' in prices.}}\n# The [[beginning]] (of the morning).\n#: {{syn|en|crack of dawn|Thesaurus:dawn}}\n#: {{co|en|[[daybreak|day'''break''']]}}\n#: {{co|en|at the '''break''' of day}}\n# An act of [[escape|escaping]].\n#: {{co|en|to make a '''break''' for it; to make a '''break''' for the door}}\n#: {{ux|en|It was a clean '''break'''.}}\n#: {{co|en|prison '''break'''}}\n# {{label|en|computing}} The separation between [[line]]s, [[paragraph]]s or [[page]]s of a written text.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2001|author=Nan Barber; David Reynolds|title=Office 2001 for Macintosh: The Missing Manual|page=138\n|passage=No matter how much text you add above the '''break''', the text after the '''break''' will always appear at the top of a new page.}}\n# {{lb|en|computing}} A [[keystroke]] or other [[signal]] that causes a [[program]] to terminate or suspend execution.\n# {{lb|en|programming}} {{ellipsis of|en|breakpoint}}.\n# {{lb|en|British|weather}} A change, particularly the end of a spell of [[persistent]] good or bad [[weather]].\n# {{lb|en|sports|_|and|_|games}}:\n## {{senseid|en|tennis}} {{lb|en|tennis}} A [[game]] won by the [[receive|receiving]] [[player]](s).\n## {{lb|en|billiards|snooker|pool}} The first [[shot]] in a game of [[billiards]].\n## {{lb|en|snooker}} The number of points scored by one player in one visit to the table.\n## {{lb|en|soccer}} The [[counter-attack]].\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 28, 2010|author=Owen Phillips| title=Sunderland 0 - 2 Blackpool| work=BBC| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9317216.stm| passage=Blackpool were not without their opportunities - thanks to their willingness to commit and leave men forward even when under severe pressure - and they looked very capable of scoring on the '''break'''.}}\n## {{lb|en|golf}} The [[curve]] imparted to the ball's motion on the [[green]] due to slope or grass texture.\n## {{lb|en|surfing}} A place where [[wave]]s break (that is, where waves [[pitch]] or [[spill]] forward creating [[white water]]).\n##: {{ux|en|The final '''break''' in the Greenmount area is Kirra Point.}}\n##* {{quote-av|en|year=1966|director={{w|Bruce Brown (director)|Bruce Brown}}|title={{w|The Endless Summer}}|text=One of the most popular summer '''breaks''' is just off to one side of the Ala Wai Yacht Harbor entrance, a spot called Ala Moana.}}\n## {{lb|en|horse racing}} The start of a horse race.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1999|author=Jay Hovdey|title=Cigar: America's Horse|page=63\n|passage=Cigar was distracted at the '''break''' and let his five opponents get the jump.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=2010|author=John Alexander|title=Exotic Wagering the Winning Way|page=60\n|passage=Perhaps it stumbles to its knees at the '''break''', effectively losing the race at the outset.}}\n## The opening of packages of cards for a [[collectible]] [[card game]], often for further distribution to paying customers.\n# {{lb|en|dated}} A large four-wheeled [[carriage]], having a straight body and [[calash]] top, with the driver's seat in front and the footman's behind.\n# {{alt form|en|brake||cart or carriage without a body, for breaking in horses}} <!--Ch1908 has both spellings-->\n# {{lb|en|equitation}} A sharp [[bit]] or [[snaffle]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1576|author=w:George Gascoigne|title=The Steele Glas\n|passage=Pampered jades {{...}} which need nor '''break''' nor bit.}}\n# {{lb|en|music}} A short section of music, often between verses, in which some performers stop while others continue.\n#: {{ux|en|The fiddle '''break''' was amazing; it was a pity the singer came back in on the wrong note.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1937|author=Ivan T. Sanderson|title=Animal Treasure|page=233|passage=The effect was weird, because with that intuitive sense possessed by the African, every drummer knew exactly when the “breaks” were coming, and whole banks of bass drums would drop out precisely on the beat.}}\n# {{lb|en|music}} The point in the musical [[scale]] at which a [[woodwind]] [[instrument]] is designed to [[overblow]], that is, to move from its lower to its upper register.\n#: {{ux|en|Crossing the '''break''' smoothly is one of the first lessons the young clarinettist needs to master.}}\n# {{lb|en|music}} The [[transition]] [[area]] between a [[singer]]'s [[vocal]] [[register]]s; the [[passaggio]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1862|title=The Serephina, Or, Christian Library of Church Music|author=John Winebrenner|url= https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/The_Seraphina_Or_Christian_Library_of_Ch/IpUhrwLx2hwC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=cross+the+break+voice+sing&pg=PA13&printsec=frontcover|page=13|passage=34. ''Of the Registers of the Voice'' - All singers have observed that there are certain parts of the Vocal Scale where a '''break''', as it is called, seldom fails to occur.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|title=The Baritone Voice: A Personal Guide to Acquiring a Superior Singing Technique|author=S. Anthony Frisella|url= https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/The_Baritone_Voice/4wNVqRG99b4C?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=cross+the+break+voice+sing&pg=PT14&printsec=frontcover|page=14|passage=The point of division between the two vocal registers is most frequently referred to as the ''register’s '''break'''''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|title=The Evolving Singing Voice: Changes Across the Lifespan|author=Karen Brunssen|url= https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/The_Evolving_Singing_Voice/phKGDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=cross+the+break+voice+sing&pg=PA76&printsec=frontcover|page=76|passage=Boys should continue in their high voice, across the '''break''' to the lower range, and end up with a voice that doesn’t have a '''break''' (Leck, 2009).}}\n# {{lb|en|geography|mostly|in the plural}} An area along a river that features steep banks, bluffs, or gorges (e.g., {{w|Upper Missouri River Breaks National Monument}}, US).\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|slang}} An [[error]]. {{defdate|late 19th–early 20th c.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1916|journal=The Saturday Evening Post|title=Three Kings and a Pair|author=w:Ring W. Lardner\n|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=g54xAQAAMAAJ&pg=GBS.RA10-PA18\n|text=\"Maybe he will some day,\" says the Missus, and then her and Bessie pretended like they'd made a '''break''' and was embarrassed.\n}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* {{sense|short section of music}} The instruments that are named are the ones that carry on playing, for example a {{m|en|fiddle break}} implies that the fiddle is the most prominent instrument playing during the break.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|title=Terms derived from ''break'' (noun)|break junction|give it a break|page break|paragraph break|potty break|section break|shelf break|tolerance break|breakless|breakly|breakproof|breaktime|crossbreak|dambreak|firebreak|lunchbreak|microbreak|minibreak|multibreak|nanobreak|newsbreak|nightbreak|shore break\n|beach break|postbreak|prebreak|shelfbreak|sunbreak|Think break\n|big break|give me a break\n|bio-break\n|Break O'Day\n|break of gauge\n|break point\n|century break|T-break\n|clean break\n|coffee break\n|daybreak\n|give someone a break<!--as in \"give me a break!\"-->\n|heartbreak\n<!--\"icebreaker\" in the sense of conversation-starter is derived from \"break the ice\"-->\n|jailbreak|ad break\n|lunch break\n|make a break for it|autumn break|Easter break|fall break\n|maximum break|Christmas break|summer break|Thanksgiving break\n|pinky break|break with tradition\n|point break|mind break\n|take a break|beambreak\n|tea break\n|bathroom break|bio break|break clause|break dance|break dancer|break dancing|break figure|break movie|break of dawn|break of day|break room|break time|break-building|break-bulk|career break|catch a break|city break|class break|comfort break|commercial break|dam break|day-break|double break|double break point|double-break|fag break|fast break|fire break|gimme a break|half-break|hammer break|harvest break|jail break|leg break|limit break|lucky break|March break|mid-term break|midterm break|mini-break|no-break space|off break|pawn break|physical break|prison break|reading break|reef break|sand break|short break|soft break|spring break|station break|syllabic break|tax break|thermal break|tie break|tie-break|toilet break|tough break|water break|wet break|wind break|wind-break|winter break|word break|word-break|zoo break|break and entry|break junction|give it a break|page break|paragraph break|potty break|section break|shelf break|tolerance break|underbreak|waterbreak|wikibreak}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n====References====\n<references/>\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{clipping|en|breakdown}} {{gloss|the percussion break of songs chosen by a DJ for use in hip-hop music}} and see also [[breakdancing]].\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|music}} {{lb|en|music}} A section of extended repetition of the [[percussion break]] to a song, created by a [[hip-hop]] [[DJ]] as [[rhythmic]] [[dance music]].\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1994|title=w:N.Y. State of Mind|album=w:Illmatic|artist=w:Nas|passage=The smooth criminal on beat '''breaks''' / Never put me in your box if your shit eats tapes}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|Amen break}}\n* {{l|en|breakcore}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|music|slang}} To [[B-boy]]; to [[breakdance]].\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1985|artist=w:Run-DMC|title={{w|King of Rock (song)|King of Rock}}|passage=Let the poppers pop and the breakers '''break''' / We're cool, cool cats, it's like that}}\n# {{lb|en|rare|mainly historical or a misspelling}} To [[brake]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1951|month=July|author=R. E. G. Read|title=From Bere Alston to Callington|journal=Railway Magazine|page=482|text='''Breaking''' heavily, now on a 1 in 39 gradient, the train makes as if to cross the Tamar at once, only to swing sharply to the right, {{...}}.}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|breaker|id=breakdancer}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n* 2001. ''The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music: North America''. Garland Publishing. Ellen Koskoff (Ed.). Pgs. 694-695.\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=abekr|Abrek|Baker|Brake|baker|barke|brake}}\n\n{{cln|en|strong verbs|contranyms|irregular verbs|terms with unraised Middle English /ɛː/}}\n{{C|en|Carriages|Ultimate}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|brèque}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-break.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Poslovitch-break.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Jérémy-Günther-Heinz Jähnick-break.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Somain>>)}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|en:break}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|break}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|break}} {{gloss|pause, holiday}}\n#: {{syn|fr|pause}}\n#: {{uxi|fr|C’est l’heure de faire un '''break'''.|It's time to take a '''break'''.}}\n# {{lb|fr|tennis}} {{l|en|break}} {{gloss|of serve}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|fr|balle de break}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n[[File:Fiat_Marengo_second_generation.jpg|thumb|un break]]\nFrom earlier {{m|fr|[[break]] de [[chasse]]}}, from {{der|fr|en|shooting brake}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|automotive}} [[estate car]], [[station wagon]]\n#: {{ant|fr|berline}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|ca|brec|bor=1}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n==Indonesian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{unadapted borrowing|id|en|break}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|id|/brek/}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{id-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|id|slang}} to break temporary in dating\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|it|ine-pro|*bʰreg-}}\n{{ubor|it|en|break}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|brèk<r:DiPI>}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|m|#}}\n\n# (''gay culture'') {{l|en|break}} (intermission or brief suspension of activity)\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|it|interjection}}\n\n# {{l|en|break}}! (boxing)\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA|breique}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Noun====\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{clipping of|pt|breakdance}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{bor+|pt|en|break}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{pt-noun|m|breaks}}\n\n# {{l|en|break}} {{gl|rest or pause}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|pt|coffee break|breque}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pt:Dicio}}\n* {{R:pt:inFormal}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|es|en|break}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr|breic}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|break}} {{gloss|pause}}\n# {{lb|es|tennis}} {{l|en|break}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}"}}